    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\n`vim.iconv()` is documented as passing encoding names through to the platform\niconv (\"whatever the iconv() library function can accept\"). But it silently\nrewrites an explicit big-endian request into the unmarked form, so the result\ndepends on the platform's iconv default instead of the byte order requested.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nRun `lua print(vim.iconv(\"test\", \"utf-8\", \"utf-16be\"))`.\n\nThis produces `<ff><fe>t^@e^@s^@t^@` on Debian (little-endian + LE BOM), `<fe><ff>^@t^@e^@s^@t`  on macOS (big-endian + BE BOM).\n\nBoth differ from the platform CLI, which emits no BOM for `iconv -f utf-8 -t utf-16be`.\n\nThis also makes vim.iconv() inconsistent with Neovim's own file writer:\n`:set fileencoding=utf-16 bomb` + `:w` produces big-endian + BOM on the same machine where vim.iconv gives little-endian.\n\nIn `src/nvim/mbyte.c`, we see that`enc_alias_table` maps \"utf-16be\" maps to IDX_UTF16, whose canonical name is \"utf-16\". enc_canonicalize() applies this before the conversion is set up, so\nthe library only ever sees \"utf-16\".\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nBig-endian, BOM-less output matching `iconv -t UTF-16BE` on every platform.\nFor contrast, `vim.iconv(\"test\",\"utf-8\",\"utf-16le\")` already works correctly.\n\n[#11960](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/11960#issuecomment-592916312) states that encoding names should be interpreted the same across platforms.\n\nAccording to `:h encoding-values`, utf-16 and utf-16le are valid values, but utf-16be is not. vim.iconv should not care about that, since it calls the platform library and should accept anything the platform iconv accepts. If instead we want to align vim.iconv with the internal file writer, we should make sure to always produce big endian output.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.13.0-dev-713+g2e8c60cb38\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nThis function does not exist in vim\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nLinux 7.0.11-arch1-1, macOS 26.4.1\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\niTerm2 3.6.11\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nother",
